THE GILIUM FRAMEWORK: A Formal State-Space Architecture for Civilizational Analysis

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

ABSTRACT

This work proposes a mathematical architecture for representing and analyzing human civilization as a dynamical system. We construct a four-dimensional bounded state-space  \mathcal{G} = [0,10]^4 \subset \mathbb{R}^4  whose axes correspond to four irreducible dimensions of social reality: Individual Interior (consciousness), Individual Exterior (behavior), Collective Interior (culture), and Collective Exterior (systems). These dimensions are derived from two primitive categorical distinctions—Individual/Collective and Interior/Exterior—whose Cartesian product yields exactly four quadrants. We treat this not as a discovered truth but as an axiomatic modeling choice, justified by phenomenological universality and mereological necessity. Every social phenomenon is understood to have a projection profile onto these four quadrants, with weights assigned via a pre‑registered procedure before empirical analysis. We define a weighted Mahalanobis metric on  \mathcal{G}  that respects the heteroscedastic uncertainty of social indicators. The dynamical core is a non-linear system  \dot{\mathbf{G}} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{G} + \mathbf{N}(\mathbf{G}) + \mathbf{E}(t) , proposed as a tractable modeling ansatz whose specific form is pragmatically justified. We introduce signed desynchronization indices— \Delta^{+}_{\text{coll}} ,  \Delta^{-}_{\text{coll}} ,  \Delta^{+}_{\text{ind}} ,  \Delta^{-}_{\text{ind}} —and embed them in a 2×2 typology of civilizational instability modes: regime crisis (institutions outpace culture), cultural fragmentation (culture outpaces institutions), anomie (behavior outpaces experience), and repressed discontent (experience outpaces behavior). Identifiability is analyzed under realistic data limitations, and formal falsifiability criteria are established, including a pre‑registration requirement for projection profiles, measurement models, and the definition of the societal unit of analysis. Worked examples—France on the eve of revolution and Weimar Germany—demonstrate the framework's operational potential with full uncertainty propagation. The Gilium framework is offered as a formal language in which empirical questions about civilizational dynamics can be posed with precision.

