Conjecture 5.1 (Regime Crisis): Societies with large and increasing  \Delta^{+}_{\text{coll}}  are vulnerable to revolutions, state collapses, and regime changes—crises of legitimacy where institutions have outpaced their cultural foundations.

Conjecture 5.2 (Cultural Fragmentation): Societies with large and increasing  \Delta^{-}_{\text{coll}}  are vulnerable to religious revivals, social movements, and tribal fragmentation—phenomena arising when cultural vitality lacks institutional embodiment.

Conjecture 5.3 (Anomie): Societies with large and increasing  \Delta^{+}_{\text{ind}}  are vulnerable to anomie, alienation, and conformity without meaning—behavioral patterns detached from subjective experience.

Conjecture 5.4 (Repressed Discontent): Societies with large and increasing  \Delta^{-}_{\text{ind}}  are vulnerable to millenarian movements, protest potential, and sudden eruptions of repressed discontent—inner experience seeking behavioral expression.

Conjecture 5.5 (General Vulnerability): The composite index  \Delta  correlates with overall systemic vulnerability, though the specific manifestation depends on which signed components dominate.

These are empirical conjectures, not mathematical theorems. They provide a rich set of testable hypotheses for future research, with clear sign-based distinctions that can be falsified.

