CHAPTER 7: FORMAL FALSIFIABILITY

7.1 The Scientific Status of the Framework

A mathematical framework is not an empirical hypothesis. But it can be falsifiable in the sense that certain empirical findings would undermine its utility or validity. Following Giere (1988), we treat the Gilium framework as a representational model whose adequacy is judged by its fit to data models, not by correspondence to some Platonic social reality. As Suppes (1962) argues in "Models of Data," the relationship between theoretical models and empirical phenomena is mediated by models of data—and it is at this level that falsification operates. To be useful, the framework must generate testable predictions about data models. This chapter specifies conditions under which the Gilium framework would be disconfirmed or require fundamental revision.

7.2 Falsification Conditions

Condition F1 (Dimensional Collapse): For a pre-registered mapping of indicators to quadrants with fixed projection profiles, if confirmatory factor analysis across diverse societies consistently yields fewer than 4 factors explaining >80% of variance, the claimed dimensionality is disconfirmed. This indicates that the four quadrants are not empirically distinguishable.

Condition F2 (Indicator Non-Convergence): If within-quadrant indicators fail to correlate (Cronbach's  \alpha < 0.5 , per Cronbach 1951) across multiple societies after pre-registered aggregation rules with fixed projection profiles, the quadrant construct lacks empirical coherence. This suggests the quadrant does not capture a unified underlying dimension. Following Borsboom, Mellenbergh & van Heerden (2003), we interpret this as evidence that the latent variable model is misspecified.

Condition F3 (Predictive Failure): For a specific, parameterized model of a particular society (e.g., the Roman Republic), if out-of-sample predictions of key events (e.g., date of transition to Empire) are systematically worse than a naive baseline (e.g., historical average) across 3+ cases, the dynamical hypothesis is disconfirmed.

Condition F4 (Metric Inconsistency): If the Mahalanobis distance yields rankings that systematically contradict expert historical judgment (e.g., hunter-gatherers consistently placed closer to industrial societies than to agricultural societies after controlling for uncertainty), the metric requires revision.

Condition F5 (Desynchronization Failure): If, across a diverse sample of historical crises, none of the signed desynchronization indices ( \Delta^{+}_{\text{coll}} ,  \Delta^{-}_{\text{coll}} ,  \Delta^{+}_{\text{ind}} ,  \Delta^{-}_{\text{ind}} ) shows systematic elevation prior to crises compared to matched non-crisis periods, in the directions predicted by Conjectures 5.1–5.4, the Desynchronization Typology is disconfirmed.

7.3 Pre-registration Requirements

To prevent post-hoc adjustment, any empirical test of F1-F5 must specify in advance:

· The indicator-to-quadrant mapping, including projection profiles for each indicator (Definition 3.3)
· The aggregation rules for obtaining quadrant scores from indicators
· The definition of the societal unit of analysis (Section 3.7)
· The societies and time periods to be included
· The success/failure criteria for each test
· Any parameters to be estimated (and priors for Bayesian analysis)

This follows best practices in quantitative social science and prevents the framework from becoming unfalsifiable through ad-hoc adjustments. The projection profile pre‑registration is particularly critical: without it, one could always reweight indicators post‑hoc to salvage convergence, violating the spirit of falsification.

7.4 Immunization Strategies (Forbidden)

The following are not permitted as defenses against falsification:

· "Pre/trans fallacy" arguments that reinterpret counter-evidence as confirmation of a higher developmental stage
· Ad hoc adjustments to indicator weights or projection profiles after seeing results
· Appeals to "higher levels" inaccessible to measurement
· Claims that the framework applies only to "developed" or "authentic" societies
· Redefining the unit of analysis after observing results

The framework stands or falls on its ability to generate coherent, testable, and (potentially) falsifiable claims about observable societies with pre‑registered specifications.

